I used the ball joints from the great Fully printable PCB Vice by Sneakypoo as a great starting point for this design.

https://www.hta3d.com/en/filament/pla-1.75mm/pla-filament-easy-printing-175mm-all-colors-materials-3d-1kg-ingeo-3d850

The camera and the DC/DC Converter will be attached with small cable ties.

title: Drop in replacement for the ultimaker extruder big wheel/gear

description.text:
The teeth of my stock plywood wheel are slowly wearing out... I'd better print a replacement now that I can ;)
This is just a use of LeemonBaird nice library with added holes (esp. the big nut slot in the center).

I printed it with 0.2mm and 1.8mm walls and 35% infill (I forgot to increase the infill, but the result seems OK so far and I have less backlash than with the stock wheel!). It took a bit less than one hour to print. Just add a flat washer, a spring washer and a butterfly nut and you have a very clean and robust setup. Update: it is now 6+ month old and it has less play, less wear and less wobble than the stock plywood gear that I used for one month or so! I added a picture for you to check (it is the one with the butterfly nut on) Update: I uploaded a new set of files (namely wheel2.scad and wheel2.stl, wheel2_internals.jpg). These are 0.5mm thicker (to make sure the captive nut may not protrude from the wheel, so the latter cannot wobble when secured tightly). I also moved the small holes outwards slightly. Now, with a 0.4 mm nozzle and 2.0mm wall thickness, these holes really touch each other, and it makes the part more robust. See the closeup picture to get the idea (wt=1.6mm, a bit too low for the next layers).

comments.text: This wheel has a different number of teeth (more) than the standard Ultimaker wheel, so I understand that it would result in a slower extrusion rate? Isn't this really a problem?

I superimposed both gears and they really match: this gear has the same geometric properties as the stock plywood gear, except for the shape of each tooth (which is better IMHO because it matches better that of the small delrin motor gear).

title: Dial caliper mounting bracket for Raise3D

description.text:
Raise3D N2 and N2 Plus printers arrives with a fully calibrated build plane, and it is really uncommon that they requires a calibration during time. But well, if for any reason it is needed to adjust the calibration (for example, prior to use a non-standard platform), then the operation is quite complex. Under the build plane there are many regulation points, each one with three different screws. A kind of nightmare, without the right tools.
The mounting bracket (modeled to hold a Borletti dial caliper), can be really useful to simplify this operation. Just mount it on the extruder assembly, and regulate each point to have the same distance from the extruder. The bracket is rigid enough to insure a very good precision, and allows to reach a tolerance of 0,01-0,02 mm. on all the build plate. The attached 3DM model allows to modify the size of the bracket to mount different dial calipers.

description.text:
Automatic drainpipe cleaner

Why?

One rainy day I was watching water coming out from a drainpipe. And I thought there's some wasted energy. It would be really cool to somehow use that for something. I kept that in my mind nearly a year until I came up with this idea. Suddenly, everything was clear.

What?

Automatic drainpipe cleaner keeps you drainpipes clear. It works on the rainy weather using the potential energy of the falling water. Note: This is a first prototype and it doesn't work as well as I was hoping. So after seeing it in action for some time I'll determine all the issues occurred and fix them in the next version.

Building the prototype

Besides all the printed parts you will need:

  • Screws size of M3 with variable lengths between 12mm to 30mm. Tip: Use nyloc nuts where ever possible.
  • Self-drilling screws
  • Ball bearings size 10mm x 15mm x 4mm
  • Some rope long enough (with a diameter of 5mm)
  • Aluminium pipes size 10mm x 1mm x 2000mm
  • Some rubber from bicycle inner tube
  • A house with drainpipes

Building it you just put all the parts together with great amount of imagination and improvisation ;)

Videos

See it in action:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5QrFTtcoNIA

description.text:
This is a replica of the Sentinel model rocket sold by Estes from 1988 through 1994. It is one of my favorite rockets. The photo shows the original Sentinel on the left, and the 3D printed version on the right. The original is 27" tall, the printed one is 21.5"

I scaled it down by .8 so the fin section would fit within the 6" diameter build plate of my Orion Delta printer. The body wall is 1 mm thick, allowing for two extrusions of .5mm.

If your printer's build plate is 8" diameter or greater, you can scale the rocket up by 1.25 in your slicer and use an extrusion width of .625 to print it at full original size.

I have not flown this rocket, so proceed at your own risk if you decide to do so. At the .8 scale, It should be possible to use BT-55 centering rings to make a motor mount that would be held in place between the bayonet fitting on the mid section and the retainer ring built into the bottom of the fin section. You would need to file/cut 4 notches in the rings to get them past the bayonet bumps in the fin section. Don't make the notches too large - you don't want the ejection gasses to escape out the rear of the rocket before they can eject the parachute! If printed with 1.25 scale multiplier, BT-60 centering rings should work. Always check your CG/CP locations !

Parts connect with bayonet fittings. Line up channels with bumps, insert and twist 90 degrees clockwise until you feel it snap in place.

The "fore" section has an internal lug that can be used to attach a shock cord. You will need to use a piece of stiff wire to thread a cord though the lug.

Printer Brand:

SeeMeCNC

Printer:

ORION Delta 3D Printer

Resolution:

Infill:

See Slic3r settings

Notes:

See included Slic3r settings zip file

Copy the Slic3r settings files into the filament/print/printer folders at
C:Users > yourID > AppData > Roaming > Slic3r

NOTE: You must print each part in the orientation shown in the second photo to avoid need for support.

The "extra length on restart" setting is necessary to maintain priming of the hot-end and avoid under-extrusion during the numerous travel moves on the fin section.

The base.stl part is the base of the nose cone - one end locks into the nose cone, the other end slip-fits into the "fore.stl" section.

If the bayonet fittings are too tight, don't force them as this can cause the plastic to friction-weld together and you might not get them apart again. Instead, use some sandpaper to sand the grooves a bit, and use a candle to rub some paraffin onto them as lubricant.

The fins have some pretty serious overhang, so the leading edge may need some post-print smoothing. If you just cannot get them to behave, you might need to go ahead and use some support. This is where you find out just how well-behaved your PLA really is. For me, the MARS PLA did really well, while the SeeMeCNC blue PLA needed a lot more cleanup.

The tip of the nose cone will likely be wobbly due to heat build-up, so be prepared to clean it up with a knife.

description.text:
Using https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2536972 Corners,
we are now going to build a 20' closed container with doors on one shortside
which, of course, can be opened.
You can also have doors on both shortsides.

You always need the same amount of Corner and Corner_mirror, because the oval
hole in the corner should be longside in the upper and lower position of the container.
So if you are building a standard container you need to print four Corner_3 and
four Corner_3_mirror.

For one sidewall you need Longside_1 at both ends and Longside_2 in the middle.
For roof it is Roof_1 at both ends and Roof_2 in the middle.

Container_Door_Hinge_B fits with A if you don't use 3D-printed doors with hinges B.
You can of course use any material for wall/roof/doors.
Hinges might need some sanding to work smoothly.

Youtube link:
https://youtu.be/S83Cjz6E4JE

Alu-profiles length for standard 20':
H: 161mm
W: 152mm
L 20': 403mm

Parts needed:
Alu-profile 10x10x1mm
Small screws
M2x8 to 10mm, four of those to door hinges.
M3x170mm threaded rod, four of those to dummy lock.
Some glue to mounting profiles, wall and roof parts.
Floor: wood, sheet metal, plastic, cardboard or whatever (or roof parts).

description.text:
I've had this wooden puzzle cube on my coffee table for years. Today, I decided to make a similar version, but with some added embellishments. I designed mine with shorter end pieces, so the overall assembled puzzle is more compact than the original wood puzzle, which is seen in the photo above.

You'll need to print 12 of the pieces to make the puzzle. For assembly instructions (cheater!) refer to this:

https://woodgears.ca/puzzles/12-piece.html

It's not identical, but the steps are exactly the same up to the way the last piece fits. This is because in his version, the cutouts on his blocks are all the same - 100mm long, divided into 5 20mm sections. Mine has three 25mm sections in the middle, and the end "caps" are 5mm. It's close enough to enable you to solve the puzzle, though.

The piece is designed with .5mm clearance on each mating face to allow for print dimension inaccuracy and ease of assembly.

Edit: v3 - shortened the ends, made the recesses a bit more shallow.

Edit: v4 - attempted putting a fillet on the edges, which turned out really badly - too many gaps between the pieces, so I scrapped v4.

Edit: v5 - increased clearance on all sides from .2mm to .5mm, redesigned the recesses, and made the ends slightly thicker to help with bed adhesion due to v3 and v4's ends curling up. Make sure you use supports so the bottom recess prints correctly!

description.text:
I tried to use the other Companion cube stickers, but I found that the square sides were not actually square. I used the extra-printable cube model to make new stickers. The square sides are 18.5mm long, which should fit the standard rubiks cube. I added holes for the hearts, lines, and circles so that colored paper can be attached on the bottom side to mark the colors.

To assemble, attach whatever colored surface you want on the bottom of the holes, then superglue to a rubiks cube.

I've successfully printed a full set in color-changed filaments. I've yet to assemble the final cube though.

.1mm

Notes:

Needs to be printed at high resolution (.1mm) since the bottoms of the pieces are quite thin.
I had some issues with the top layers, so I bumped infill to 35% and did top/bottom at .5mm

Print either 6 sides, or 24 each corner, edge and 6 middles. ( I'd suggest printing 7 sides to have extras)

at .1mm layer heights, the first two layers will be flat. I changed filament from gray to white before layer 3 to get the right cube colors.

With two layers of grey, the flats are too transparent for me, so I'm going to paint the underside grey, just to make it opaque.

I found that I can just superglue the pieces to a rubik's cube and the original sticker colors peek through the slots and holes.

description.text:
Ever find that your screwdrivers are either too big or too small?
Do you have a collection of 1/4" hex bits not being used?
This handle is designed to accept short and long hex bits.

The bits are held tight in the handle so they can be collected on an as-needed basis.
Or print them slightly over-sized to allow easy bit changes.
As a bonus, I've included a "persuader" for those places where you need the torque but lack the space to get a good grip on the handle.

It is okay to force the bit into the handle using an appropriate hammer.
These handles are pretty tough regardless of your print settings.

...and for those with a keen engineering eye; this also makes for a decent 3D printed spline drive.

Also note some strange voids within the handle print. These are in place to ensure connecting the OD with the ID. If you modify this part, please keep this in mind.

A 5x5x5cm weighted companion cube, designed specifically for the Prusa Multi-material printer.

This is designed to locate into the truss rod/screw holes on the headstock stump, with string tension clamping it onto the end. Once the high and low string are in, it does not move.

Screws are required, which clamp down onto the strings inside the adapter and stop them sliding out under tension.

This was modelled after a "proper" single ball adapter such as:

description.text:
This is a management tool to use with BreakoutEDU kits or similar lock out games. Many teachers use a "ticket" system with paper tickets and a complicated chart to track multiple groups using one break out box. I found it very difficult to facilitate the breakout AND manage the lock progress. This puts the tracking in the hands of the students or makes it easy for an assistant or parent helper. I created these color coded "lock rings" to be placed on the lock shackle. I assign a color to each group and print one set of lock rings in each assigned color. ( I typically have 30-36 students in a class and run 6 groups of 5-6 students per group, my colors are ROYGBP) I place one color coded ring per group on the corresponding shackle. title: Prusa MMU - Right Angle Extruder Bracket

description.text:
A bracket for the Prusa "MultiMaterial Upgrade", allowing the extruders to be perpendicular to the top frame.

This is helpful if an enclosure is being used (i.e. IKEA Lack, cabinet, etc...), and there isn't much headroom for the PTFE tubes to angle upwards. The PTFE tubes just barely come over the top of the frame.

Extruder frame is 24mm (~1") above the frame
PTFE tubes are ~1mm above the frame

WARNING: The extruder frame is rotated with the motors facing down, this causes the extruders to be in reverse order (4321, instead of 1234). This will require some amount of experience to rewire the extruders in this way, as it differ's from Prusa's assembly instructions.

WARNING: as pointed out by @ir_fuel, the ptfe tubes can bind some when the extruder reaches max Z height. The useable print height is decreased when using this print, so be aware of that if you use this modification.

Pre-Installation Steps:

  1. All filament is removed from the printer and extruders.
  2. Printer power is off.
  3. Extruder wires are unplugged from Stepper Switch Board, and freely hanging.
  4. PTFE Tubes are removed from the Festo plugs on the Extruder Body.
  5. The angle bracket has been removed from one or both Extruder Body (If you have the 2 or 4 extruder version.)
  6. Print one or two of the "Right Angle Extruder Bracket" beforehand.

"Right Angle Extruder Bracket" Installation:

Step 1:
Screw the "Right Angle Extruder Bracket" to the Extruder Body using 10mm M2 screws. Ensure the bracket is facing towards the motors, so the motors will face downwards when attached to the top frame.

Step 2:
Place the Extruder Body on the top frame, aligning them so the extruder motors are facing downwards.

Step 3:
Plug the motors back into the Stepper Switch Boards in the following order:
(This is from the front perspective of the printer.)

  • 1st motor from the right is plugged into Port E0
  • 2nd motor from the right is plugged into Port E1
  • 3rd motor from the right is plugged into Port E2
  • 4th motor from the right is plugged into Port E3

Perform any cable management to keep the extruder wires out of the way of printing.

Step 4:
Reinstall the PTFE tubing into the Festo plugs on the Extruder Body.

Post-Installation Testing:

After installation is complete, and all extruders are plugged back into the Stepper Switch Board. Power on the printer, and prepare to some filament to be loaded.

Perform the necessary steps to load filament into each extruder. Ensuring the filament is properly fed into the PTFE tubes.

Keep in mind that the extruder order is now: 4, 3, 2, 1

Troubleshooting

Filament is not pulled into the tubing and begins to strip:
Check that the motors are not reversed. This can happen if the extruder with 2 dots is plugged into an odd numbered Port # on the Stepper Switch Board. Example: 2 dot motor plugged into Port E1 is incorrect.

title: Hybrid Dual Color Single Hot End Extruder

description.text:
Revision1 - Sep. 25, 2017: Update Idle (it was wrong); Upload funky big gear; loaded new 3d views.

This is a remix from Nophead's mendel90 wades extruder. (Made for E3D v6) with Prusa i3 MK2 Multi Material Y- Piece

Simple idea to convert your printer into a duo material. This Hybrid model combines a Directdrive for the everyday print (maybe flexibles) and a Bowden extruder for the second material.

Both gears are exactly the same as original NopeHead's design
Use 4mm O.D. tubing to create the filament path inside the block, where the melting filament is "parking" wile the other material prints. OR BETTER, if you use 1/8" O.D. aluminum round tube (3/32" I.D.), Prusa MM uses this method.
Idle uses wood type screws ( trying to keep weight to a minimum)
Uses 3 small bearing, 688 (8mm I.D. x 16mm O.D. x 5mm width)
Need 1 hobbed bolt. Same spec than Mendel 90 by NopeHead's design.
Bowden fittings are M6. (trough fitting recommended)
The file has build in support. (I tried to keep-up with Nopehead's highest standards)

Marlin must support multi extruder with a single hot end feature.
Prometheus extruder web site has a good guide for upgrading Marlin.

Tip: tubing that goes inside E3D hot end should have an "spot" with I.D. around 1.8mm. removing the chance of a bigger head filament when retracting. ( I put a "dent" in mine with the help of drill to spin the tube wile round finger plyers put a dent on it)

Still a work in progress, I will put it toguether when my new step motors show up, I will upload some pictures then. The pictures of printings you see are from my previous extruder project that I have not published, but uses the same system.

description.text:
I was given a Creality CR-10 to play with, so I wanted something to test. The included sample file is apparently a 10 hour print, so I didn't want to jump in with that. I want to do another Baby Groot (I gave mine away), but was impatient to see how the printer did, so I made it smaller.

I've included 3 sizes, plus the version I was scaling before drilling the holes.

Printer:

Creality CR-10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2mm (Standard)

Infill:

15%

Notes:

This was my test piece for my new Creality CR-10. I figured infill didn't matter much, could probably do without it, but I set it to 15% just for grins.

Printed in PLA with no modifications to the stock printer on the included painter's type tape.

I use Simplify 3D for most of my printing, and it has a profile for the CR-10. By default it wanted 2400mm/min, which is slower than my other printer's 3600mm/min. I didn't like how slow the first print was, so I changed it to 3600mm/min for the second print.

It took ~1.5 hours to print a small + large keychain version at the 3600mm/min (60mm/second) setting.

Full disclosure: Gearbest gave me the CR-10, so I feel sort of obligated to put it through it's paces.

I took the other Baby Groot's, shoved the head onto the body in Microsoft 3D Builder, got rid of a ton of the polygons, and then shoved a hole in it's head.

The 30mm tall one seemed a bit small, so I made a 60mm version. That seems a little big, so there's a 45mm version as well. They're all just scaled versions of each other, except for where I manually placed the hole. I also included my starting point without the hole as a 3D Builder 3mf file.

3D Builder seems pretty good for these kinds of simple mashups.

I like this pose, but it might not be the best for a keychain the way the fingers poke out, I may need to try a different version.
